            ],
            "abstractNote": "Conceptual and phenomenological macroecological models of current global ﬁre activity have demonstrated the overwhelming control exerted by primary productivity. Fire activity is very high in savanna regions with intermediate primary productivity, and very low in both densely forested regions with high productivity and arid/cold regions with low productivity. However, predicting future global ﬁre activity using such macroecological models of ﬁre’s global ‘niche’ may not be possible because of the feedbacks between ﬁre, climate and vegetation that underpin the ﬁre− productivity relationship. Improving forecasts of global ﬁre activity demands the use of dynamic models to determine how climate, CO2, vegetation (i.e. canopy closure and plant functional types) and primary productivity constrain ﬁre and evaluation of the strength of feedbacks amongst these variables.",
